<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870707-0012 </DOCNO><HL> What's News --Business andamp; Finance</HL><DD> 07/07/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><TEXT>   CHRYSLER AGREED to pay $1.6 million to settle federal charges of health and safety violations in the workplace. The penalty, the largest in OSHA history, reflects the agency's crackdown on employer violations. It also is the second agency fine involving Chrysler in recent months.    ---   The Thompson family's planned purchase of Southland Corp. for $4 billion will force the firm to reverse its diversification strategy and pare down to its 7-Eleven stores, distribution centers and 50% Citgo stake.    ---   A global ban on farm subsidies by the year 2000 was formally proposed by the U.S. But the idea faces such stiff opposition at home and abroad that any pact is unlikely soon.    ---   The White House may drop efforts to have Congress enact changes in the budget process as part of an increase in the debt ceiling, sources said.    ---   Allegis plans to cut 250 management-level jobs at United Air as part of a major restructuring of the unit. The moves further consolidate the authority of Chairman Frank Olson.    ---   U.S. crude oil prices surged to nearly $21 a barrel on spot and futures markets. Traders cited growing worries about tensions in the Persian Gulf as well as other factors.    ---   U.S. car sales fell 13.8% in late June from a strong year-ago period. But the results represented an improvement from the weak sales pace of May and early June.    ---   Ontario's investigation into possible insider-trading activity is touching nearly every major Canadian securities firm, according to sources.    ---   ZZZZ Best sued its founder and former chairman, along with four others, charging fraud in the alleged payment of $18 million for work that wasn't done. The carpet-cleaning firm also says it plans to file for Chapter 11.    ---   Gerber Products' president and chief executive, Leo D. Goulet, died after an apparent heart attack Sunday. The news reignited takeover rumors about the baby food maker.    ---   Dainippon Ink andamp; Chemicals indicated it may sweeten its $473 million hostile bid for Reichhold Chemicals. But Reichhold said it is stepping up efforts to find other buyers.    ---   CBS became the second network to cancel its TV ratings contract with A.C. Nielsen, citing dissatisfaction with the new &quot;people meter.&quot;    ---   The European Community opened two dumping investigations against Japan and South Korea.    ---   The plastics industry is rebounding after a decade-long lull, reflecting increased demand, a decline in oil prices and a weaker dollar.    ---   Mortgage rates rose slightly last week, to an average 10.36% on a 30-year, fixed-rate loan. But rates are expected to ease in coming months.    ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 155,010,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials 2429.53, off 7.17; transportation 1021.73, off 8.70; utilities 204.97, off 0.93.    Bonds: Shearson Lehman Treasury index 1307.27, up 2.81.    Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 126.14, up 0.06; spot index 128.80, up 0.31.    Dollar: 148.90 yen, up 0.14; 1.8373 marks, off 0.0025. </TEXT></DOC>